<TITLE> Start of Gulistan flyover work postponed </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 11 (bdnews24.com)--The start of work of long-awaited Jatrabari-Gulistan flyover, scheduled for May 13, has been postponed as the local government minister is now abroad. "The local government department on Tuesday decided to postpone the inauguration works due to minister Syed Ashraful Islam being out of the country," said Miznur Rahman, assistant personal secretary to the state minister for local government Jahangir Kabir Nanok. He said a fresh inauguration date would be fixed after the minister's coming home. The inauguration was postponed at a time when Dhaka City Corporation, the project implementing agency, and contactor Belhasa Acom and Associate, had taken all preparations and even printed invitation cards. The DCC decided in 2003 to build the flyover and Belhasa ACOM was given work order for the project on June 21, 2005 following an international tender. The contactor started works on the project in June, 2006 but the caretaker government stopped the works for alleged irregularities in the contact awarding process. Local partners of Belhasa went into hiding during the caretaker government, which conducted an anti-corruption purge during its 2007-08 regime. The Awami League government took initiatives to resume works of the project after coming to power in 2009. Local entrepreneurs of Belhasa are now implementing the project as their Dubai-based partners had abandoned the project due to its uncertainty, Belhasa Acom and Associate managing director Salman Karim told bdnews24.com. He said three local banks are financing it. The around nine-kilometer flyover is being built as a priority project under the government's multi-dimensional plan to ease the city's traffic congestions. Karim said India's Simplex Infrastructure Ltd, experienced in flyover building, would offer them technical support to implement the projec
